sentence: Crude oil futures off the lows after U.S. factory data .
Investing.com - Crude oil futures trimmed losses during U.S. morning trade on Tuesday , after official data showed that U.S. factory orders rose by the most in five months in February .
On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light sweet crude futures for delivery in May traded at USD96 .47 a barrel during U.S. morning trade , down 0.65 % on the day .
New York-traded oil prices fell by as much as 1.2 % earlier in the session to hit a daily low of USD95 .93 a barrel .
Nymex oil came off the lowest level of the session after the U.S. Census Bureau said factory orders rose by a seasonally adjusted 3 % in February , compared to expectations for an increase of 2.9 % .

The data came one day after the Institute of Supply Management said its U.S. manufacturing purchasing managers ' index declined to 51.3 in March , its lowest level since December , from 54.2 in February .
Market players now looked ahead to the release of fresh weekly information on U.S. stockpiles of crude and refined products to gauge the strength of oil demand in the world 's largest oil consumer .
The American Petroleum Institute will release its inventories report later in the day , while Wednesday 's government report could show crude stockpiles rose by 2.3 million barrels .
The U.S. is the world 's biggest oil consuming country , responsible for almost 22 % of global oil demand .
Oil prices came under pressure after weak manufacturing data out of the U.K. and the euro zone fuelled concerns over the outlook for global growth .
Revised data showed that manufacturing activity in the euro zone contracted for the 20th consecutive month in March , while the U.K. manufacturing sector shrank for the second straight month .
Sentiment also remained fragile amid concerns over the potential implications of a bailout for Cyprus .

Elsewhere , on the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for May delivery dipped 0.4 % to trade at USD110 .67 a barrel , with the spread between the Brent and crude contracts standing at USD14 .20 a barrel .

The spread between the two contracts continued to trade near an eight-month low , due to an improving production outlook in the North Sea and amid growing concerns over the euro zone 's economic outlook .
At the same time , U.S. oil stockpiles at Cushing , Oklahoma , the delivery point for Nymex oil futures , are declining as new pipelines relieve a supply glut there .
